    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1952-01-05T18:36:00-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1952-01-05T18:36:00-05:00" n="633"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d633">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">690D.91/1–552: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The <gloss type="from">Secretary of State</gloss> to the
                            <gloss type="to">Embassy in India</gloss>
                    </hi>
                    <note n="1" xml:id="d633fn1">This telegram was repeated for information to Paris
                        (for the delegation at the General Assembly), Karachi, and London.</note>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <seg rendition="#left">
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">secret</hi>
                    </seg>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Washington</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1952-01-05T18:36:00-05:00"
                            >January 5, 1952—6:36 p.m.</date>
                    </dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>1335. Re Kashmir. <gloss target="#t_Dept1">Dept</gloss>’s further reaction
                        <persName corresp="#p_BSGS1">Bajpai</persName>’s suggestion <gloss
                        target="#t_Deptel1">Deptel</gloss> 1295 Dec 31, contained <gloss
                        target="#t_Embtel1">Embtel</gloss>s 2224 Dec 26,<note n="2" xml:id="d633fn2">
                        <ref target="frus1951v06p2#pg_1925">
                            <hi rend="italic">Foreign Relations</hi>, 1951, vol. <hi
                                rend="smallcaps">vi</hi>, Part 2, p. 1925</ref>.</note> 2273 Dec 29,
                    2299 Jan 2 follows: <list>
                        <label>1.</label>
                        <item>
                            <gloss target="#t_Dept1">Dept</gloss> suspects <persName
                                corresp="#p_BSGS1">Bajpai</persName>’s proposals may be motivated by
                                <gloss target="#t_GOI1">GOI</gloss> desire delay <gloss
                                target="#t_SC1">SC</gloss> res further and allow contd consolidation
                                <term target="#t_IN1">Ind</term> position Kashmir. <gloss
                                target="#t_GOI1">GOI</gloss> may well have in mind a further
                            spinning out process in which additional delays will be sought. If this
                            true <persName corresp="#p_BSGS1">Bajpai</persName>’s suggestions will
                            provide mechanism for further delay and avoid possible <gloss
                                target="#t_SC1">SC</gloss> action at this stage.</item>
                        <label>2.</label>
                        <item>Nevertheless we do not wish pass over any possible opportunity
                            afforded by <gloss target="#t_GOI1">GOI</gloss> to reach settlement and
                            in view strong <gloss target="#t_Emb1">Emb</gloss> recommendations
                            contained <gloss target="#t_Embtel1">Embtel</gloss> 2299 Jan 2 <gloss
                                target="#t_Dept1">Dept</gloss> suggests fol informal approach to
                                <persName corresp="#p_BSGS1">Bajpai</persName> by <gloss
                                target="#t_Amb1">Amb</gloss> with implication clear that approach
                            being made under <gloss target="#t_instrs1">instrs</gloss>: <list>
                                <label>
                                    <hi rend="italic">a</hi>)</label>
                                <item>During long history negots on this issue <gloss
                                        target="#t_Dept1">Dept</gloss> has been frankly disappointed
                                    in past that after being led believe more conciliatory attitude
                                    was developing on part of Ind, attitude had stiffened. <gloss
                                        target="#t_FYI1">FYI</gloss>
                                    <persName corresp="#p_BSGS1">Bajpai</persName> strongly
                                    intimated to <gloss target="#t_Dept1">Dept</gloss> officials in
                                    Oct 1949 that <term target="#t_IN1">Ind</term> wld <pb
                                        facs="0116" n="1166" xml:id="pg_1166"/> agree to partition
                                    with a plebiscite in the Vale<note n="3" xml:id="d633fn3">For
                                        documentation, see <ref target="frus1949v06#pg_1686">
                                            <hi rend="italic">Foreign Relations</hi>, 1949, vol. <hi
                                                rend="smallcaps">vi</hi>, pp. 1686</ref> ff.</note>
                                    which <gloss target="#t_IN1">Ind</gloss> subsequently rejected
                                    when presented by <persName>Dixon</persName>.<note n="4"
                                        xml:id="d633fn4">Sir <persName>Owen Dixon</persName> of
                                        Australia had been appointed UN Representative for India and
                                        Pakistan by the Security Council on Apr. 12, 1950, in
                                        accordance with the Council’s resolution of Mar. 14, 1950
                                        (UN doc. S/1461). <persName>Dixon</persName> reported to the
                                        Security Council on Sept. 15, 1950 that no agreement had
                                        been reached between India and Pakistan for the
                                        demilitarization of the State of Jammu and Kashmir or on
                                        other preparations for the holding of a free and impartial
                                        plebiscite and requested the formal termination of his
                                        position. (UN doc. S/1791)</note> End <gloss
                                        target="#t_FYI1">FYI</gloss>.</item>
                                <label>
                                    <hi rend="italic">b</hi>)</label>
                                <item>US wld be prepared support <persName corresp="#p_BSGS1"
                                        >Bajpai</persName>’s suggestion re continuation <persName
                                        corresp="#p_GDF1">Graham</persName>’s mediatory activities
                                    until Mar first if we have clear assurance re change of <gloss
                                        target="#t_GOI1">GOI</gloss> attitude to indicate more
                                    responsiveness to <persName corresp="#p_GDF1">Graham</persName>
                                    proposals. Minimum indication along this line wld be agreement
                                    to pt 10 of <persName corresp="#p_GDF1">Graham</persName>
                                    proposals in Dec 18 report (appt of <gloss target="#t_PlebAd1"
                                        >PlebAd</gloss>).<note n="5" xml:id="d633fn5">UN doc.
                                        S/2448.</note> We believe such undertaking wld be conducive
                                    to quicker settlement re nr troops to remain at end
                                    demilitarization period.</item>
                                <label>
                                    <hi rend="italic">c</hi>)</label>
                                <item>If <gloss target="#t_GOI1">GOI</gloss> reaction negative we
                                    see likely end utility <persName corresp="#p_GDF1"
                                        >Graham</persName> in a mediatory role. In this event there
                                    wld seem to be no alternative but for <gloss target="#t_SC1"
                                        >SC</gloss> to take further action which might well have
                                    unfortunate effect placing India in unfavorable light.</item>
                            </list>
                        </item>
                        <label>3.</label>
                        <item>While <gloss target="#t_Dept1">Dept</gloss> does not intend discuss
                            foregoing approach with UK until after your reply recd, <gloss
                                target="#t_Dept1">Dept</gloss> leaves your discretion whether you
                            discuss matter with Nye before or after your talk with <persName
                                corresp="#p_BSGS1">Bajpai</persName>.</item>
                        <label>4.</label>
                        <item>
                            <gloss target="#t_FYI1">FYI</gloss> only, if <gloss target="#t_GOI1"
                                >GOI</gloss> reaction negative we have in mind, provided UK agrees,
                            urging <persName corresp="#p_GDF1">Graham</persName> make final appeals
                            in person to <persName corresp="#p_NJ1">Nehru</persName> and <persName
                                corresp="#p_NK1">Nazimuddin</persName> for acceptance his proposals
                            prior tabling <gloss target="#t_SC1">SC</gloss> res. In this connection
                            we wld hope <persName corresp="#p_GDF1">Graham</persName> visit wld last
                            approx 10 days in which he wld visit both capitals. <gloss
                                target="#t_Dept1">Dept</gloss> believes best time <persName
                                corresp="#p_GDF1">Graham</persName> approach <persName
                                corresp="#p_NJ1">Nehru</persName> wld be about Feb 1 after <gloss
                                target="#t_IN1">Ind</gloss> elections and before convening <gloss
                                target="#t_IN1">Ind</gloss> Parliament. In event <persName
                                corresp="#p_GDF1">Graham</persName> unsuccessful <gloss
                                target="#t_Dept1">Dept</gloss> wld join UK in sponsoring <gloss
                                target="#t_SC1">SC</gloss> res which wld presumably recommend
                            parties accept <persName corresp="#p_GDF1">Graham</persName>
                            proposals.</item>
                        <label>5.</label>
                        <item>In using phrase “if India were not asked to compromise too large nr of
                            troops” (<gloss target="#t_Embtel1">Embtel</gloss> 2274 [<hi
                                rend="italic">2273</hi>]) <gloss target="#t_Dept1">Dept</gloss>
                            assumes <persName corresp="#p_BSGS1">Bajpai</persName> meant withdraw.
                            In this connection <persName corresp="#p_GDF1">Graham</persName> of
                            opinion <gloss target="#t_IN1">Ind</gloss> figures much too large and he
                            continues believe highly desirable have minimum mil forces on both
                            sides. Presence large nr of troops wld in <gloss target="#t_Dept1"
                                >Dept</gloss>’s view lessen chances fair plebiscite. Re <persName
                                corresp="#p_BSGS1">Bajpai</persName> statement India “might allow
                                <gloss target="#t_PlebAd1">PlebAd</gloss> to have final decision on
                            placing these troops” <gloss target="#t_GOI1">GOI</gloss> has already
                            agreed per sec 4<hi rend="italic">a</hi> Jan 5 1949 Res:<note n="6"
                                xml:id="d633fn6">The UN Commission for India and Pakistan (<gloss
                                    target="#t_UNCIP1">UNCIP</gloss>) Resolution of Jan. 5, 1949,
                                which set down the conditions and basic principles of the proposed
                                plebiscite (UN doc. S/1196).</note> “<gloss target="#t_PlebAd1"
                                >PlebAd</gloss> will determine in consultation with <gloss
                                target="#t_GOI1">GOI</gloss> the final disposal of <gloss
                                target="#t_IN1">Ind</gloss> and State Armed Forces…”<note n="7"
                                xml:id="d633fn7">Ellipsis appears in the source text.</note>
                        </item>
                        <label>6.</label>
                        <item>
                            <gloss target="#t_Dept1">Dept</gloss> believes inadvisable future
                            conversations with <gloss target="#t_IN1">Ind</gloss> officials to make
                            any <gloss target="#t_ref1">ref</gloss> to “pressure from <gloss
                                target="#t_Pak1">Pak</gloss>.” Only pressure officially acknowledged
                            by US is obligation work for just solution this dispute accordance with
                            UN principles.</item>
                        <pb facs="0117" n="1167" xml:id="pg_1167"/>
                        <label>7.</label>
                        <item>Re para 2 <gloss target="#t_Embtel1">Embtel</gloss> 2224 you may in
                            your discretion ask <persName corresp="#p_BSGS1">Bajpai</persName> what
                            he meant specifically by “extending <persName corresp="#p_GDF1"
                                >Graham</persName>’s terms of <gloss target="#t_ref1">ref</gloss> as
                            far as possible.” Re para 3 <gloss target="#t_Dept1">Dept</gloss>
                            believes question <persName corresp="#p_GDF1">Graham</persName>’s mtg
                            both Prime Ministers might well be left <persName corresp="#p_GDF1"
                                >Graham</persName>’s decision.</item>
                    </list>
                </p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <persName corresp="#p_ADG1">
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Acheson</hi>
                        </persName>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
    </text>
